The Data

In this lab weâre going look at the median weekly cost of childcare in California. A detailed description of the data can be found here.

The data come to us from TidyTuesday.

0. Load the appropriate libraries and the data.

Code 
library(tidyverse)
library(forcats)
Code 
childcare_costs <- read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2023/2023-05-09/childcare_costs.csv')

counties <- read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2023/2023-05-09/counties.csv')

1. Briefly describe the dataset (~ 4 sentences). What information does it contain?

In this lab weâre going look at the median weekly cost of childcare in California.

The childcare_costs dataset looks at various counties and provides information on unemployement rates, labor force participation rates, poverty rates, medium earnings/ income, total population count, race, number of households, employement/ type of jobs, and chilcare care rates for different groups. The counties dataset looks at various counties and provides information on their name, state, and two letter abbreviation. Together, these datasets allow us to analyze and compare counties in terms of employment, poverty, household income, and childcare costs, offering insights into the economic factors that may influence childcare affordability across different regions.

California Childcare Costs

Letâs start by focusing only on California.

2. Create a ca_childcare dataset of childcare costs in California, containing (1) county information and (2) all information from the childcare_costs dataset. Hint: There are 58 counties in CA and 11 years in the dataset. Therefore, your new dataset should have 53 x 11 = 638 observations.

ca_childcare <- childcare_costs |>
  inner_join(counties, by = "county_fips_code") |>
  filter(state_abbreviation == "CA")

3. Using a function from the forcats package, complete the code below to create a new variable where each county is categorized into one of the 10 Census regions in California. Use the Region description (from the plot), not the Region number.
Hint: This is probably a good place to use ChatGPT to reduce on tedious work. But you do need to know how to prompt ChatGPT to make it useful!

Code 
# https://chatgpt.com/share/670f53c2-5bec-8006-9ff7-68ad14bbe154
# Looked up what function could be helpful here

ca_childcare <- ca_childcare |> # keep
  mutate(county_name = str_remove(county_name, " County")) |> # keep
  mutate(region = 
    fct_collapse(county_name,
      "1" = c("Butte", "Colusa", "El Dorado", "Glenn", "Lassen", "Modoc", "Nevada", "Placer", 
              "Plumas", "Sacramento", "Shasta", "Sierra", "Siskiyou", "Sutter", "Tehama", "Yolo", "Yuba"),
      "2" = c("Del Norte", "Humboldt", "Lake", "Mendocino", "Napa", "Sonoma", "Trinity"),
      "3" = c("Alameda", "Contra Costa", "Marin", "San Francisco", "San Mateo", "Santa Clara", "Solano"),
      "4" = c("Alpine", "Amador", "Calaveras", "Madera", "Mariposa", "Merced", "Mono", "San Joaquin", 
              "Stanislaus", "Tuolumne"),
      "5" = c("Monterey", "San Benito", "San Luis Obispo", "Santa Barbara", "Santa Cruz", "Ventura"),
      "6" = c("Fresno", "Inyo", "Kern", "Kings", "Tulare"),
      "7" = c("Riverside", "San Bernardino"),
      "8" = c("Los Angeles"),
      "9" = c("Orange"),
      "10" = c("Imperial", "San Diego")
  ))

4. Letâs consider the median household income of each region, and how that income has changed over time. Create a table with ten rows, one for each region, and two columns, one for 2008 and one for 2018. The cells should contain the median of the median household income (expressed in 2018 dollars) of the region and the study_year. Arrange the rows by 2018 values.

Code 
# https://chatgpt.com/share/670f5a38-d3b4-8006-ad62-8769382ddacb
# got a red error from rstudio -- asked what it means -- added .groups = 'drop'

ca_childcare |>
  filter(study_year == 2008 | study_year == 2018) |>
  group_by(region, study_year) |>
  summarise(median_income = median(mhi_2018, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = 'drop') |>
  pivot_wider(id_cols = region,
              names_from = study_year, 
              values_from = median_income, 
              names_prefix = "Income ") |>
  arrange(`Income 2018`)

5. Which California region had the lowest median full-time median weekly price for center-based childcare for infants in 2018? Does this region correspond to the region with the lowest median income in 2018 that you found in Q4?
Hint: The code should give me the EXACT answer. This means having the code output the exact row(s) and variable(s) necessary for providing the solution.

The region with the lowest medium full-time median weekly price for center-based childcare for infants in 2018 is group 1, and in the previous datatset the second to lowest group is group 1 (the lowest is group 6).

Code 
 ca_childcare |>
  filter(study_year == 2018) |>
  group_by(region) |>
  summarise(med_price = median(mc_infant, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = 'drop') |>
  slice_min(med_price)

Code 
# https://chatgpt.com/share/6710bf20-da7c-8006-9a2d-850e8997cd0a
# Chat GPT: Looked up examples and applied them to my code on my
# Looked up what "loess smoother"
# Looked up how to put graphs next to each other -- facet_wrap()
# Looked up how to change axis -- make y go up by 100 (start at 100, end at 500)
# and the x axis so it includes 2008-2018 and goes up by 2 years
# Looked up how to separate graphs a little
# Looked up how to adjust size of text and line/ dots
# Looked up how to change text size

ca_childcare_long <- ca_childcare |>
  select(study_year, region, mc_infant, mc_toddler, mc_preschool) |>
  # columns that start with mc_ should be made into a new column (combined)
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("mc_"), 
               # call this new column age that will hold ^ 
               names_to = "age", 
               # new column price that will hold corresponding value
               values_to = "price") |>
  mutate(recode(age, mc_infant = "Infant", 
                     mc_toddler = "Toddler", 
                    mc_preschool = "Preschooler"),
         factor(age, levels = c("Infant", "Toddler", "Preschooler")))

Code 
ggplot(ca_childcare_long, aes(x = study_year, y = price, color = region)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", linewidth = 0.5) +  
  geom_point(size = 0.8) + 
  # creates seperate graphs for age_groups
  # each has its own x-axis
  # in one row 
  facet_wrap(~ age, scales = "free_x", nrow=1) +  
  labs(title = "Weekly Median Price for Center-Based Childcare ($)",
       x = "Study Year",
       y = "",
       color = "California Region") +
  # adjust axis
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(100, 500), breaks = seq(100, 500, by = 100)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2008, 2018, by = 2)) +
  # spaces the graphs apart, lines is a unit
  theme(panel.spacing = unit(1, "lines"), 
        # change size of graphs
        aspect.ratio = 1, 
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 6), 
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 6))

Median Household Income vs.Â Childcare Costs for Infants

7. Create a scatterplot showing the relationship between median household income (expressed in 2018 dollars) and the full-time median weekly price charged for center-based childcare for an infant in California. Overlay a linear regression line (lm) to show the trend.

Code 
ggplot(ca_childcare, aes(x = mhi_2018, y = mc_infant)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +  
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "steelblue") + 
  labs(
    title = "Correlation Between Household Income 
    and Center-Based Childcare Costs in California",
    y = "",
    x = "2018 Dollars",
    subtitle = "Median Weekly Price for Infants"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

8. Look up the documentation for lm() and fit a linear regression model to the relationship shown in your plot above.

Code 
# complete the code provided

reg_mod1 <- lm(mc_infant ~ mhi_2018, data = ca_childcare)

9. Using the output from summary(), write out the estimated regression line (recall: \(y = mx + b\)).

y = (2.241e-03)x + 1.317e+02

10. Do you have evidence to conclude there is a relationship between the median household income and the median weekly cost of center-based childcare for infants in California? Cite values from your summary() output to support your claim!

Yes. The slope is positive, so if the average income a household makes increases, the weekly cost of infant childcare also increases. More specifically, the slope is 2.241e-03, meaning that for every dollar a household makes, the weekly cost of infant goes up by about $0.002241. Next, the p-value is < 2.2e-16, which is smaller than 0.05, which further proves that statistically there is a relationship between childcare prices and income. The t-value for the mhi_2018 coefficient is 33.26 (t-value for slope), which is large, suggesting the slope is far from 0, or that again household income does have an impact on childcare cost. Lastly, the R-sqaured value is 0.635, so 63.5% of the childcare cost variability is a result from income.

## The Data

In this lab we're going look at the median weekly cost of childcare in
California. A detailed description of the data can be found [here](https://github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/blob/master/data/2023/2023-05-09/readme.md).

The data come to us from [TidyTuesday](https://github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday).

**0. Load the appropriate libraries and the data.**

```{r}
#| label: setup
#| echo: true
#| warning: false
#| message: false

library(tidyverse)
library(forcats)
```

```{r}
#| label: load-data
#| echo: true
#| warning: false
#| message: false

childcare_costs <- read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2023/2023-05-09/childcare_costs.csv')

counties <- read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2023/2023-05-09/counties.csv')
```

**1. Briefly describe the dataset (~ 4 sentences). What information does it contain?**

In this lab weâre going look at the median weekly cost of childcare in California.

The childcare_costs dataset looks at various counties and provides information on
unemployement rates, labor force participation rates, poverty rates, medium earnings/
income, total population count, race, number of households, employement/ type of jobs, 
and chilcare care rates for different groups. The counties dataset looks at various 
counties and provides information on their name, state, and two letter abbreviation. 
Together, these datasets allow us to analyze and compare counties in terms of 
employment, poverty, household income, and childcare costs, offering insights into 
the economic factors that may influence childcare affordability across different 
regions.

## Median Household Income vs. Childcare Costs for Infants

**7. Create a scatterplot showing the relationship between median household income (expressed in 2018 dollars) and the full-time median weekly price charged for center-based childcare for an infant in California. Overlay a linear regression line (lm) to show the trend.**

```{r}
#| label: scatterplot-median-income-vs-childcare-cost
#| echo: true
#| warning: false
#| message: false

ggplot(ca_childcare, aes(x = mhi_2018, y = mc_infant)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +  
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "steelblue") + 
  labs(
    title = "Correlation Between Household Income 
    and Center-Based Childcare Costs in California",
    y = "",
    x = "2018 Dollars",
    subtitle = "Median Weekly Price for Infants"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()  
```

**8. Look up the documentation for `lm()` and fit a linear regression model to the relationship shown in your plot above.**

```{r}
# complete the code provided
#| echo: true
#| warning: false
#| message: false

reg_mod1 <- lm(mc_infant ~ mhi_2018, data = ca_childcare)
summary(reg_mod1)
```

**9. Using the output from `summary()`, write out the estimated regression line (recall: $y = mx + b$).**

y = (2.241e-03)x + 1.317e+02

**10. Do you have evidence to conclude there is a relationship between the median household income and the median weekly cost of center-based childcare for infants in California? Cite values from your `summary()` output to support your claim!**

Yes. The slope is positive, so if the average income a household makes increases, 
the weekly cost of infant childcare also increases. More specifically, the slope is 
2.241e-03, meaning that for every dollar a household makes, the weekly cost of 
infant goes up by about $0.002241. Next, the p-value is < 2.2e-16, which is
smaller than 0.05, which further proves that statistically there is a relationship
between childcare prices and income. The t-value for the mhi_2018 coefficient is 33.26
(t-value for slope), which is large, suggesting the slope is far from 0, or that
again household income does have an impact on childcare cost. Lastly, the R-sqaured
value is 0.635, so 63.5% of the childcare cost variability is a result from 
income.
